{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/hearing-loss-in-adults/background-information/prognosis/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"db2818cc-2c7f-5c6b-9063-6eb4814ca532","slug":"prognosis","fullItemName":"Prognosis","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 42531610-e26e-4a66-b04d-aac500df75f9 --><h2>What is the prognosis?</h2><!-- end field 42531610-e26e-4a66-b04d-aac500df75f9 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 044742e8-d1b0-467a-8e51-aac500df75c2 --><!-- begin field 417358af-ff97-49c8-bb4b-aac500df75f9 --><p>Prognosis is dependent on the underlying cause — early identification and treatment may prevent or limit morbidity.</p><ul><li><strong>Conductive hearing loss</strong><ul><li>Many causes of conductive hearing loss can be treated with full return to usual hearing (for example uncomplicated infections of the outer or middle ear and wax impaction).</li><li>Some causes of conductive hearing loss such necrotising otitis externa can be life-threatening if not identified and treated early.</li><li>For more information, see the sections on prognosis in the CKS topics on <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/cholesteatoma/\">Cholesteatoma</a>, <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/earwax/\">Earwax</a>, <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/otitis-externa/\">Otitis externa</a> and <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/otitis-media-acute/\">Otitis media - acute</a>.</li></ul></li></ul><ul><li><strong>Sensorineural hearing loss</strong><ul><li>Hearing loss associated with ageing and/or excessive noise (the most common causes) is usually slowly progressive over time and permanent.</li><li>Sudden sensorineural hearing loss (SSNHL)<ul><li>Hearing loss due to SSNHL can range from mild to profound and be temporary or permanent.</li><li>Between 32% and 65% of cases of SSNHL recover spontaneously — prognosis is thought to be related to a variety of factors including age, co-existence of vertigo, degree of hearing loss, and duration between onset of hearing loss and treatment [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/hearing-loss-in-adults/references/\">Stachler, 2012</a>].</li><li>A meta-analysis including 10 studies (n=4,814) found that people with SSNHL associated with vertigo had worse hearing recovery than SSNHL without vertigo (42.13% for those with SSNHL and vertigo compared to 60.29% for those with SSNHL without vertigo [OR 2.22; 95% CI 1.54-3.20]) [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/hearing-loss-in-adults/references/\">Yu, 2018</a>].</li><li>Early intervention with steroids is the mainstay of treatment.</li></ul></li><li>Meniere’s disease<ul><li>For more information on the prognosis of Meniere’s disease, see the CKS topic on <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/menieres-disease/\">Meniere&#39;s disease</a></li></ul></li></ul></li></ul><p>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/hearing-loss-in-adults/references/\">Phan, 2016</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/hearing-loss-in-adults/references/\">Cunningham, 2017</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/hearing-loss-in-adults/references/\">NICE, 2018</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/hearing-loss-in-adults/references/\">Michels, 2019</a>] </p><!-- end field 417358af-ff97-49c8-bb4b-aac500df75f9 --><!-- end item 044742e8-d1b0-467a-8e51-aac500df75c2 -->","topic":{"id":"04ebfcd5-34b5-50ed-9f39-eb5d18a386dd","topicId":"2f4e8b5b-3e3c-4daf-95b5-aa0600bd0fb1","topicName":"Hearing loss in adults","slug":"hearing-loss-in-adults","lastRevised":"Last revised in September 2019","chapters":[{"id":"6f91987e-3ad1-50d2-9fa8-cb374f1fea65","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","sub